05086nam a22007215i 9780824863142DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20042004hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248631427 a10.1515/97808248631422doi  a(DE-B1597)484243  a(OCoLC)1024020960  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aDS916.55.D83 2005eb 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a341.261 aDudden, Alexis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJapan’s Colonization of Korea :bDiscourse and Power /cAlexis Dudden. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b9 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Illegal Korea -- t2. International Terms of Engagement -- t3. The Vocabulary of Power -- t4. Voices of Dissent -- t5. Mission Législatrice -- tCoda: A Knowledgeable Empire -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its creation in the early twentieth century, policymakers used the discourse of international law to legitimate Japan’s empire. Although the Japanese state aggrandizers’ reliance on this discourse did not create the imperial nation Japan would become, their fluent use of its terms inscribed Japan’s claims as legal practice within Japan and abroad. Focusing on Japan’s annexation of Korea in 1910, Alexis Dudden gives long-needed attention to the intellectual history of the empire and brings to light presumptions of the twentieth century’s so-called international system by describing its most powerful—and most often overlooked—member’s engagement with that system.Early chapters describe the global atmosphere that declared Japan the legal ruler of Korea and frame the significance of the discourse of early twentieth-century international law and how its terms became Japanese. Dudden then brings together these discussions in her analysis of how Meiji leaders embedded this discourse into legal precedent for Japan, particularly in its relations with Korea. Remaining chapters explore the limits of these ‘universal’ ideas and consider how the international arena measured Japan’s use of its terms. Dudden squares her examination of the legality of Japan’s imperialist designs by discussing the place of colonial policy studies in Japan at the time, demonstrating how this new discipline further created a common sense that Japan’s empire accorded to knowledgeable practice. This landmark study greatly enhances our understanding of the intellectual underpinnings of Japan’s imperial aspirations. In this carefully researched and cogently argued work, Dudden makes clear that, even before Japan annexed Korea, it had embarked on a legal and often legislating mission to make its colonization legitimate in the eyes of the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLawzJapanxHistory. 0aLawzKoreaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486314240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824863142423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824863142/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (